00:51:56,850 --> 00:51:59,040
look at things off in the horizon.

1263
00:51:59,040 --> 00:52:00,980
If you're walking or hiking or biking,

1264
00:52:00,980 --> 00:52:02,530
not looking at your phone the whole time

1265
00:52:02,530 --> 00:52:03,620
that you're doing that.

1266
00:52:03,620 --> 00:52:06,270
If you're at the bus
stop or you're commuting,

1267
00:52:06,270 --> 00:52:07,970
certainly not looking at your phone

1268
00:52:07,970 --> 00:52:10,240
the entire time you're doing that.

1269
00:52:10,240 --> 00:52:11,530
So this is vital.

1270
00:52:11,530 --> 00:52:13,800
And I want to emphasize another protocol,

1271
00:52:13,800 --> 00:52:15,340
though I don't want to get
into it in too much depth,

1272
00:52:15,340 --> 00:52:16,173
'cause I want to make sure

1273
00:52:16,173 --> 00:52:18,810
that I also talk about a number
of other important aspects

1274
00:52:18,810 --> 00:52:21,370
of the visual system that
are more related to sight,

1275
00:52:21,370 --> 00:52:25,960
but getting into optic
flow is very important

1276
00:52:25,960 --> 00:52:28,253
for de-stressing your system.

1277
00:52:29,410 --> 00:52:30,760
When you move through space,

1278
00:52:30,760 --> 00:52:34,610
whether or not it's through
walking, biking, even swimming,

1279
00:52:34,610 --> 00:52:37,520
if it's self-generated optic flow,

1280
00:52:37,520 --> 00:52:40,110
so probably not driving or motorcycling,

1281
00:52:40,110 --> 00:52:43,840
but yes, bicycling or I
don't know, unicycling.

1282
00:52:43,840 --> 00:52:44,980
I don't know why I
thought about unicycling.

1283
00:52:44,980 --> 00:52:46,320
There used to be a graduate
student at Stanford

1284
00:52:46,320 --> 00:52:47,670
who was a really impressive unicycler,

1285
00:52:47,670 --> 00:52:48,770
those are pretty rare.

1286
00:52:49,940 --> 00:52:51,960
As long as it's self-generated optic flow,

1287
00:52:51,960 --> 00:52:54,550
meaning you're generating
motion of your body

1288
00:52:54,550 --> 00:52:56,570
and the visual images around you

1289
00:52:56,570 --> 00:52:58,840
are passing by on your eyes,

1290
00:52:58,840 --> 00:53:00,940
that is very good for the visual system.

1291
00:53:00,940 --> 00:53:03,010
And it's very good for the mood systems

1292
00:53:03,010 --> 00:53:05,100
and the neuromodulator
systems of the brain and body

1293
00:53:05,100 --> 00:53:06,310
that regulate mood.

1294
00:53:06,310 --> 00:53:08,240
This is well-established.

1295
00:53:08,240 --> 00:53:10,320
So I'm not telling people to get away

1296
00:53:10,320 --> 00:53:11,440
from their phone and their computers.

1297
00:53:11,440 --> 00:53:13,670
I spend a lot of time staring at a page,

1298
00:53:13,670 --> 00:53:16,570
drawing, writing, texting,
et cetera, just like you do,

1299
00:53:16,570 --> 00:53:20,080
but we're really talking about
some very simple protocols

1300
00:53:20,080 --> 00:53:22,240
that aren't just designed
to improve your sleep,

1301
00:53:22,240 --> 00:53:26,335
but are really designed to
bolster and enhance your vision.

1302
00:53:26,335 --> 00:53:28,010
And of course, because it's this podcast,

1303
00:53:28,010 --> 00:53:29,270
we will also talk about things

1304
00:53:29,270 --> 00:53:31,050
that you can take to improve your vision.

1305
00:53:31,050 --> 00:53:35,140
But if your visual behavior isn't right,

1306
00:53:35,140 --> 00:53:37,360
and I do believe we should
always start with behaviors,

1307
00:53:37,360 --> 00:53:39,930
and then think about nutrition,
supplementation, et cetera,

1308
00:53:39,930 --> 00:53:42,140
if your behaviors around
vision aren't right,

1309
00:53:42,140 --> 00:53:45,270
you cannot expect to have
good, healthy eyesight

1310
00:53:45,270 --> 00:53:48,600
for a long time, meaning
throughout your lifespan.

1311
00:53:48,600 --> 00:53:50,410
And if your vision is already poor,

1312
00:53:50,410 --> 00:53:52,860
many of these things that
I'm talking about today,

1313
00:53:52,860 --> 00:53:53,693
perhaps all of them,

1314
00:53:53,693 --> 00:53:56,510
will improve your vision to some degree.

1315
00:53:56,510 --> 00:53:59,070
And if your vision is starting to go,

1316
00:53:59,070 --> 00:54:00,910
then doing these behaviors

1317
00:54:00,910 --> 00:54:03,940
is likely to really enhance
the quality of the vision

1318
00:54:03,940 --> 00:54:06,660
that you will build
and maintain over time.

1319
00:54:06,660 --> 00:54:09,820
And all of these are
essentially zero cost, okay?

1320
00:54:09,820 --> 00:54:11,770
If you live in a very dark environment,

1321
00:54:11,770 --> 00:54:14,770
like a cave or outer space,

1322
00:54:14,770 --> 00:54:16,560
it's going to be hard to
do some of this stuff.

1323
00:54:16,560 --> 00:54:20,610
But if you're on planet earth,
even if there's cloud cover,

1324
00:54:20,610 --> 00:54:23,000
chances are you can do some, or most,

1325
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:26,110
or even all of these
some, most, or all days.

1326
00:54:26,110 --> 00:54:27,450
What I'm about to describe next

1327
00:54:27,450 --> 00:54:30,030
is going to seem so
silly on the face of it,

1328
00:54:30,030 --> 00:54:32,083
but has deep mechanism to support it.

1329
00:54:33,360 --> 00:54:37,923
Put simply, when you get
tired, your eyelids close,

1330
00:54:39,040 --> 00:54:41,323
and when you're alert,
your eyelids are open.

1331
00:54:42,450 --> 00:54:46,490
That is because you have
neurons in your brain,

1332
00:54:46,490 --> 00:54:49,110
that depending on your level of alertness,

1333
00:54:49,110 --> 00:54:52,193
will make it easy or hard
to keep your eyes open.

1334
00:54:53,090 --> 00:54:55,230
Now, that's a complete duh,

1335
00:54:55,230 --> 00:54:57,350
except that we don't often
think about the relationship

1336
00:54:57,350 --> 00:55:01,423
between alertness and where we
are looking and our eyelids.

1337
00:55:02,450 --> 00:55:05,270
Now, I learned this from a
colleague of mine in psychiatry,

1338
00:55:05,270 --> 00:55:06,520
who happens to work on hypnosis.

1339
00:55:06,520 --> 00:55:07,950
I'm not going to hypnotize you right now.

1340
00:55:07,950 --> 00:55:10,350
That's actually for a future episode.

1341
00:55:10,350 --> 00:55:14,550
But what happens when we get tired?

1342
00:55:14,550 --> 00:55:17,173
Our eyelids close, and
our chin moves down.

1343
00:55:18,200 --> 00:55:20,100
We tend to nod out this way.

1344
00:55:20,100 --> 00:55:22,920
If you have ever been in a classroom,

1345
00:55:22,920 --> 00:55:24,080
certainly not one of mine,

1346
00:55:24,080 --> 00:55:25,940
but if you've been in a classroom

1347
00:55:25,940 --> 00:55:28,340
and the lecturer is kind of drawing on,

1348
00:55:28,340 --> 00:55:29,720
or it's the afternoon,

1349
00:55:29,720 --> 00:55:31,300
what you'll notice is
that a number of students,

1350
00:55:31,300 --> 00:55:35,360
their heads are jolt, kind
of their eyelids are closing,

1351
00:55:35,360 --> 00:55:37,100
and their chin is dropping, and they,

1352
00:55:37,100 --> 00:55:39,200
you'll see a bunch of heads
bouncing back up, right?

1353
00:55:39,200 --> 00:55:41,590
I was definitely one of
those people in class.

1354
00:55:41,590 --> 00:55:43,930
If it was post-lunch in the afternoon,

1355
00:55:43,930 --> 00:55:46,630
it's warm, the hum of the air conditioner,

1356
00:55:46,630 --> 00:55:49,263
or whatever it is, and I'm just out, okay?

1357
00:55:50,540 --> 00:55:53,380
When we're wide awake,
the opposite happens.

1358
00:55:53,380 --> 00:55:56,470
Our eyelids are open all the way,

1359
00:55:56,470 --> 00:55:58,280
and our chin happens to be up.

1360
00:55:58,280 --> 00:56:01,280
And no, this is not me telling
you to have good posture.

1361
00:56:01,280 --> 00:56:04,750
However, what I learned from
my colleague at Stanford

1362
00:56:04,750 --> 00:56:08,610
is that these circuits
actually act in loops.

1363
00:56:08,610 --> 00:56:13,610
When we look up, maybe it's
because these melanopsin cells

1364
00:56:13,680 --> 00:56:15,690
are in the bottom of our retina, they are,

1365
00:56:15,690 --> 00:56:17,270
and maybe it's because they're there

1366
00:56:17,270 --> 00:56:21,750
in order to view sunlight,
which is overhead, which it is,

1367
00:56:21,750 --> 00:56:24,420
but that system of alertness

1368
00:56:24,420 --> 00:56:26,620
is linked to the position of our eyes.

1369
00:56:26,620 --> 00:56:28,550
So when we look up and our eyelids are up,

1370
00:56:28,550 --> 00:56:31,550
it actually has a purpose.

1371
00:56:31,550 --> 00:56:35,680
It actually creates a
wakefulness signal for the brain.

1372
00:56:35,680 --> 00:56:37,330
And so, while this might seem like

1373
00:56:37,330 --> 00:56:38,930
the silliest and simple tool

1374
00:56:38,930 --> 00:56:41,300
that I might ever
describe on this podcast,

1375
00:56:41,300 --> 00:56:45,870
if you are feeling tired, it
actually can be beneficial

1376
00:56:45,870 --> 00:56:47,550
to the wakefulness systems of the brain,

1377
00:56:47,550 --> 00:56:48,940
including the locus coeruleus

1378
00:56:48,940 --> 00:56:51,050
and these areas that
release norepinephrine

1379
00:56:51,050 --> 00:56:52,570
to actually look up,

1380
00:56:52,570 --> 00:56:54,660
to actually look up toward the ceiling.

1381
00:56:54,660 --> 00:56:56,420
You don't want your chin all the way back,

1382
00:56:56,420 --> 00:56:59,530
but to look up and to raise
your eyes toward the ceiling

1383
00:56:59,530 --> 00:57:02,970
and to look up and try and
hold that for 10 to 15 seconds.

1384
00:57:02,970 --> 00:57:04,810
So this isn't looking up
and closing your eyes,

1385
00:57:04,810 --> 00:57:07,150
like on a nice sunny day, that's relaxing.

1386
00:57:07,150 --> 00:57:11,160
This is looking up and actually
looking up at the ceiling.

1387
00:57:11,160 --> 00:57:13,720
It actually triggers some
of the areas of the brain

1388
00:57:13,720 --> 00:57:15,430
that are involved in wakefulness.

1389
00:57:15,430 --> 00:57:18,260
So if you're somebody who's
falling asleep at your work,

1390
00:57:18,260 --> 00:57:20,260
this can be very beneficial.

1391
00:57:20,260 --> 00:57:25,260
Likewise, many people are
looking at their phone all day,

1392
00:57:26,750 --> 00:57:28,410
and their chin is down,

1393
00:57:28,410 --> 00:57:29,900
and then they're sitting at a computer

1394
00:57:29,900 --> 00:57:31,040
that's positioned below them,

1395
00:57:31,040 --> 00:57:34,010
and they're having trouble
staying awake or focusing.

1396
00:57:34,010 --> 00:57:36,180
It can be very, I tell
Costello this all the time,

1397
00:57:36,180 --> 00:57:37,170
'cause he's always falling asleep

1398
00:57:37,170 --> 00:57:38,410
while he's trying to do his work,

1399
00:57:38,410 --> 00:57:42,920
positioning your computer
screen up at eye level,

1400
00:57:42,920 --> 00:57:46,410
or sometimes having it
actually above eye level,

1401
00:57:46,410 --> 00:57:49,150
can actually create
wakefulness and alertness

1402
00:57:49,150 --> 00:57:50,440
for the work that you're going to do.

1403
00:57:50,440 --> 00:57:53,270
This is simply because of this connection

1404
00:57:53,270 --> 00:57:55,010
between the brainstem circuits

1405
00:57:55,010 --> 00:57:58,380
and the other neural circuits
that control wakefulness

1406
00:57:58,380 --> 00:58:01,970
and eyelids opening and looking up.

1407
00:58:01,970 --> 00:58:04,520
Okay, so it, again,
it's remarkably simple,

1408
00:58:04,520 --> 00:58:06,610
almost laughably simple, but it's grounded

1409
00:58:06,610 --> 00:58:08,630
in some of the most hardwired,

1410
00:58:08,630 --> 00:58:09,830
meaning present from birth,

1411
00:58:09,830 --> 00:58:12,200
aspects of our neural circuitry.

1412
00:58:12,200 --> 00:58:15,520
And norepinephrine released
from locus coeruleus

1413
00:58:15,520 --> 00:58:16,990
isn't just a mouthful,

1414
00:58:16,990 --> 00:58:21,020
it's a really interesting
and powerful mechanism

1415
00:58:21,020 --> 00:58:22,650
for how the rest of the brain wakes up.

1416
00:58:22,650 --> 00:58:25,290
Locus coeruleus hoses
the rest of your brain

1417
00:58:25,290 --> 00:58:29,020
with norepinephrine, in order
to wake up those circuits

1418
00:58:29,020 --> 00:58:30,240
for work and attention.

1419
00:58:30,240 --> 00:58:34,230
And so, eyes up is actually a way,

1420
00:58:34,230 --> 00:58:36,590
a route into increased alertness.

1421
00:58:36,590 --> 00:58:39,530
Eyes down is a route into sleepiness,

1422
00:58:39,530 --> 00:58:41,550
into reduced alertness.

1423
00:58:41,550 --> 00:58:45,373
And I have only one
friend that texts up here,

1424
00:58:45,373 --> 00:58:47,520
like on the street
holds his phone up here.

1425
00:58:47,520 --> 00:58:49,040
It looks ridiculous.

1426
00:58:49,040 --> 00:58:52,340
And yet, you know, if we were trying

1427
00:58:52,340 --> 00:58:54,140
to create more sense of alertness,

1428
00:58:54,140 --> 00:58:55,340
if that's your goal,

1429
00:58:55,340 --> 00:58:58,560
positioning computer
screens up high, chin up,

1430
00:58:58,560 --> 00:59:01,330
looking up if you need to kind
of create an alertness signal,

1431
00:59:01,330 --> 00:59:03,640
not always being chin down and texting,

1432
00:59:03,640 --> 00:59:06,800
or working into typewriters,
or reading below us.

1433
00:59:06,800 --> 00:59:10,470
is actually going to send a
recurring wakefulness signal.

1434
00:59:10,470 --> 00:59:11,870
When things are up, we tend to be alert.

1435
00:59:11,870 --> 00:59:14,190
When everything's focused
down, including our eyes,

1436
00:59:14,190 --> 00:59:15,720
it tends to have a more suppressive

1437
00:59:15,720 --> 00:59:17,490
or sedative type signaling

1438
00:59:17,490 --> 00:59:19,180
to the deeper centers of the brain.

1439
00:59:19,180 --> 00:59:22,170
Now, before we move on to
the science, and tools,

1440
00:59:22,170 --> 00:59:24,690
and protocols related to pattern vision,

1441
00:59:24,690 --> 00:59:26,850
I want to mention another
study that was done

1442
00:59:26,850 --> 00:59:28,460
by the University of Pennsylvania.

1443
00:59:28,460 --> 00:59:31,730
They have a terrific group
there that works on sleep.

1444
00:59:31,730 --> 00:59:33,410
They made an important discovery

1445
00:59:33,410 --> 00:59:35,810
that I think everybody should know about,

1446
00:59:35,810 --> 00:59:39,950
which is that children that sleep in rooms

1447
00:59:39,950 --> 00:59:44,900
that have a nightlight or dim
lights are much more likely

1448
00:59:44,900 --> 00:59:47,563
to develop myopia, nearsightedness.

1449
00:59:48,840 --> 00:59:53,130
Conversely, children that
sleep in very dark rooms,

1450
00:59:53,130 --> 00:59:57,653
so either very dim
nightlights or complete black,

1451
00:59:58,530 --> 01:00:01,460
they have a much lower,
statistically speaking,

1452
01:00:01,460 --> 01:00:03,170
a significantly lower probability

1453
01:00:03,170 --> 01:00:06,160
of developing myopia, nearsightedness.

1454
01:00:06,160 --> 01:00:08,000
Now, why is that?

1455
01:00:08,000 --> 01:00:12,440
It's because the wavelengths
of light that matter

1456
01:00:12,440 --> 01:00:14,233
for these melanopsin cells,

1457
01:00:15,160 --> 01:00:17,623
oftentimes can get through the eyelids.

1458
01:00:18,660 --> 01:00:21,880
And that's particularly true for children

1459
01:00:21,880 --> 01:00:23,810
and people that have thin eyelids.

1460
01:00:23,810 --> 01:00:26,400
Some people, like me,
have very thin eyelids.

1461
01:00:26,400 --> 01:00:27,983
I've been told this before.

1462
01:00:28,830 --> 01:00:30,180
Not many people touch my eyelids,

1463
01:00:30,180 --> 01:00:33,570
but among those that have,
I have very thin eyelids.

1464
01:00:33,570 --> 01:00:36,830
I notice I have very thin eyelids
compared to say, Costello.

1465
01:00:36,830 --> 01:00:38,240
Now, Costello's eyes droop.

1466
01:00:38,240 --> 01:00:40,660
He can't even close his eyes
all the way they're so droopy.

1467
01:00:40,660 --> 01:00:43,640
But many people have thin eyelids,

1468
01:00:43,640 --> 01:00:45,700
and those people are going
to be even more prone

1469
01:00:45,700 --> 01:00:48,280
to light coming in through the eyelid.

1470
01:00:48,280 --> 01:00:52,580
So for parents, for kids, and for adults,

1471
01:00:52,580 --> 01:00:54,980
you really want to try to get to a place

1472
01:00:54,980 --> 01:00:57,410
where you can sleep in a completely black

1473
01:00:57,410 --> 01:00:58,960
or dark environment.

1474
01:00:58,960 --> 01:01:00,930
One little exposure to light, no big deal.

1475
01:01:00,930 --> 01:01:03,650
But this ties back to the other protocol

1476
01:01:03,650 --> 01:01:06,460
that I've described before in
the mood and sleep episodes,

1477
01:01:06,460 --> 01:01:08,630
which is that viewing light,

1478
01:01:08,630 --> 01:01:10,290
even a very low intensity

1479
01:01:10,290 --> 01:01:12,450
between the hours of 10:00 PM and 4:00 AM

1480
01:01:12,450 --> 01:01:14,490
is extremely detrimental to the dopamine

1481
01:01:14,490 --> 01:01:17,150
and other mood producing
systems of the brain.

1482
01:01:17,150 --> 01:01:19,760
It can negatively impact
learning, and immunity,

1483
01:01:19,760 --> 01:01:21,220
and even blood sugar,

1484
01:01:21,220 --> 01:01:23,400
and make people type two diabetes prone

1485
01:01:23,400 --> 01:01:26,160
by way of communication
from these melanopsin cells

1486
01:01:26,160 --> 01:01:28,700
to a structure in the
brain called the habenula.

1487
01:01:28,700 --> 01:01:30,540
Why am I throwing out all this verbiage?

1488
01:01:30,540 --> 01:01:32,450
Well, because people have
asked for more mechanisms.

1489
01:01:32,450 --> 01:01:33,470
So, if you really want to know,

1490
01:01:33,470 --> 01:01:35,250
when you look at blue light

1491
01:01:35,250 --> 01:01:37,010
or if blue light is getting
in through your eyelids

1492
01:01:37,010 --> 01:01:38,340
in the middle of the night,

1493
01:01:38,340 --> 01:01:39,970
it is likely distorting

1494
01:01:39,970 --> 01:01:43,630
this lens accommodation
mechanism in the eye

1495
01:01:43,630 --> 01:01:47,260
and leading to myopia in some cases.

1496
01:01:47,260 --> 01:01:49,427
So, that's one reason to
avoid blue light exposure

1497
01:01:49,427 --> 01:01:51,440
and bright light exposure,
even nightlight exposure,

1498
01:01:51,440 --> 01:01:52,750
in middle of the night.

1499
01:01:52,750 --> 01:01:55,340
Viewing any light of bright intensity

1500
01:01:55,340 --> 01:01:58,030
between the hours of 10:00 PM and 4:00 AM

1501
01:01:58,030 --> 01:02:01,040
on a consistent basis is
going to suppress dopamine,

1502
01:02:01,040 --> 01:02:02,680
because of the way that that light

1503
01:02:02,680 --> 01:02:04,170
activates these melanopsin cells,

1504
01:02:04,170 --> 01:02:06,770
and the habenula, and the dopamine system.

1505
01:02:06,770 --> 01:02:08,680
So it's all very simple,

1506
01:02:08,680 --> 01:02:12,290
get as much bright light
as you can safely, right?

1507
01:02:12,290 --> 01:02:13,800
You never want to look
at any light so bright

1508
01:02:13,800 --> 01:02:16,760
that it's painful look
at, during the daytime.

1509
01:02:16,760 --> 01:02:18,960
Try and go without sunglasses,
unless you need them.

1510
01:02:18,960 --> 01:02:21,110
Now, I wear sunglasses for sake of sport

1511
01:02:21,110 --> 01:02:23,180
and sake when it's really bright out,

1512
01:02:23,180 --> 01:02:25,040
but I try to get two hours a day

1513
01:02:25,040 --> 01:02:27,370
of working outside or being outside,

1514
01:02:27,370 --> 01:02:30,730
even if there's cloud cover,
that's going to offset myopia.

1515
01:02:30,730 --> 01:02:32,330
It's going to help you get better sleep.

1516
01:02:32,330 --> 01:02:35,310
It's going to support mood
and metabolism, et cetera.

1517
01:02:35,310 --> 01:02:37,500
And at night, if you're sleeping

1518
01:02:37,500 --> 01:02:38,560
with a lot of lights in the room,

1519
01:02:38,560 --> 01:02:41,450
and especially, if there are
kids that need a nightlight,

1520
01:02:41,450 --> 01:02:43,900
you should try and wean
them off that nightlight,

1521
01:02:43,900 --> 01:02:45,240
because it's going to be beneficial

1522
01:02:45,240 --> 01:02:47,310
for their vision to wean
them off that nightlight

1523
01:02:47,310 --> 01:02:49,270
and put them into a darker environment.

1524
01:02:49,270 --> 01:02:50,880
Obviously, you want to get
them emotionally comfortable

1525
01:02:50,880 --> 01:02:52,480
with that first.

1526
01:02:52,480 --> 01:02:56,020
Now, let's talk about pattern
vision, actual seeing things,

1527
01:02:56,020 --> 01:02:58,040
like faces and colors, et cetera.

1528
01:02:58,040 --> 01:03:01,280
I'm presuming that some of
you out there are colorblind.

1529
01:03:01,280 --> 01:03:05,290
We can all help the red-green
colorblind folks out there

1530
01:03:05,290 --> 01:03:08,690
by not using red in slides and diagrams,

1531
01:03:08,690 --> 01:03:10,230
and on menus, and things of that sort.

1532
01:03:10,230 --> 01:03:12,030
Try and use magenta instead.

1533
01:03:12,030 --> 01:03:15,560
They can see the contrast
between magenta and green

1534
01:03:15,560 --> 01:03:19,010
better than if there's red and green.

1535
01:03:19,010 --> 01:03:21,160
So, be kind to the
colorblind folks out there.

1536
01:03:21,160 --> 01:03:23,080
It's actually a fair percentage.

1537
01:03:23,080 --> 01:03:24,960
And there are a lot of
different kinds of colorblind.

1538
01:03:24,960 --> 01:03:28,310
I should just mention some
people are true monochromats.

1539
01:03:28,310 --> 01:03:29,700
They see the world in black and white.

1540
01:03:29,700 --> 01:03:31,263
That's exceedingly rare.

1541
01:03:32,120 --> 01:03:35,150
Most colorblind people,
colorblind in quotes,

1542
01:03:35,150 --> 01:03:36,900
are red-green colorblind,

1543
01:03:36,900 --> 01:03:39,680
meaning they lack red cone photo pigment,

1544
01:03:39,680 --> 01:03:42,130
meaning they can't see
long wavelengths of light.

1545
01:03:42,130 --> 01:03:45,550
So they see the world much
as a canine or a cat does,

1546
01:03:45,550 --> 01:03:48,270
where they don't get
the green-red contrast.

1547
01:03:48,270 --> 01:03:50,540
That's why we call it
red-green colorblind.

1548
01:03:50,540 --> 01:03:52,000
They have the green cones,

1549
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:54,030
but they can't do the contrast comparison

1550
01:03:54,030 --> 01:03:56,720
that I described at the
beginning of the episode.

1551
01:03:56,720 --> 01:04:00,450
So use magenta, and they
will be able to see things.

1552
01:04:00,450 --> 01:04:02,440
You wonder why stop signs and stop lights

1553
01:04:02,440 --> 01:04:03,940
and things aren't in magenta.

1554
01:04:03,940 --> 01:04:05,410
Well, because the world is unkind

1555
01:04:05,410 --> 01:04:07,800
to the red-green color blind individuals,

1556
01:04:07,800 --> 01:04:09,860
and they have to learn the
position of those lights

1557
01:04:09,860 --> 01:04:11,400
in the street lights.

1558
01:04:11,400 --> 01:04:13,440
And they have to learn
the shapes of signs,

1559
01:04:13,440 --> 01:04:14,360
which they can do readily,

1560
01:04:14,360 --> 01:04:16,740
and it usually says stop on it as well.

1561
01:04:16,740 --> 01:04:19,660
But if you care about
colorblind folks, which I do,

1562
01:04:19,660 --> 01:04:21,290
then we could all do them a service

1563
01:04:21,290 --> 01:04:24,620
by, I think by law actually in the U.S.,

1564
01:04:24,620 --> 01:04:27,363
menus are required to be
colorblind accessible.

1565
01:04:28,890 --> 01:04:31,500
How can you improve your vision?

1566
01:04:31,500 --> 01:04:34,010
How can you get better at seeing things?

1567
01:04:34,010 --> 01:04:35,980
Well, one way is to make sure

1568
01:04:35,980 --> 01:04:39,390
that you spend at least
10 minutes a day total,

1569
01:04:39,390 --> 01:04:42,330
at least, viewing things
off in the distance.

1570
01:04:42,330 --> 01:04:45,420
So that would be well
over half a mile or more,

1571
01:04:45,420 --> 01:04:46,760
try and see a horizon,

1572
01:04:46,760 --> 01:04:50,110
try and get your vision out to a location

1573
01:04:50,110 --> 01:04:53,103
that's beyond the four walls
of your house or apartment,

1574
01:04:53,990 --> 01:04:56,700
or the doors of your car, and
the windshield of your car.

1575
01:04:56,700 --> 01:04:59,390
I know that can be hard to
do, but it's very valuable.

1576
01:04:59,390 --> 01:05:00,980
If you live in a city like New York

1577
01:05:00,980 --> 01:05:02,860
and it's skyscrapers everywhere,

1578
01:05:02,860 --> 01:05:04,130
you've probably experienced

1579
01:05:04,130 --> 01:05:06,380
the incredible sense of relaxation,

1580
01:05:06,380 --> 01:05:08,110
and it's aesthetically beautiful,

1581
01:05:08,110 --> 01:05:10,270
when you are walking down
one of these long avenues,

1582
01:05:10,270 --> 01:05:12,150
and you turn, and I think they have

1583
01:05:12,150 --> 01:05:14,100
a name for this in New York,

1584
01:05:14,100 --> 01:05:17,580
where the sunset is suddenly visible

1585
01:05:17,580 --> 01:05:20,330
along a long avenue
between some skyscrapers.

1586
01:05:20,330 --> 01:05:22,320
And it's just very relaxing to be able,

1587
01:05:22,320 --> 01:05:23,750
suddenly, to see at a distance,

1588
01:05:23,750 --> 01:05:25,870
and that's actually
because this eye mechanism

1589
01:05:25,870 --> 01:05:28,180
of relaxing the lens

1590
01:05:29,200 --> 01:05:32,310
and relaxing some of the
musculature around the eyes

1591
01:05:32,310 --> 01:05:34,060
sends signals deep into the brainstem

1592
01:05:34,060 --> 01:05:35,450
that release some of the centers

1593
01:05:35,450 --> 01:05:39,100
that are involved in
alertness, AKA stress.

1594
01:05:39,100 --> 01:05:40,920
And it's very pleasant for a reason.

1595
01:05:40,920 --> 01:05:45,290
It's not a, it's not a
placebo effect if you will.

1596
01:05:45,290 --> 01:05:46,570
There are a bunch of neurochemicals

1597
01:05:46,570 --> 01:05:48,340
and things that are associated with that.

1598
01:05:48,340 --> 01:05:49,860
So try and see at a distance,

1599
01:05:49,860 --> 01:05:51,420
because it's good for your eyesight.

1600
01:05:51,420 --> 01:05:54,060
It'll keep this lens nice and elastic,

1601
01:05:54,060 --> 01:05:56,690
and the muscles nice and
strong that move the lens,

1602
01:05:56,690 --> 01:06:00,510
and it has this relaxing component to it.

1603
01:06:00,510 --> 01:06:05,090
Now, our visual system is
exquisitely tuned to motion,

1604
01:06:05,090 --> 01:06:07,130
not just our self-generated motion,

1605
01:06:07,130 --> 01:06:08,920
but the motion of things around us.

1606
01:06:08,920 --> 01:06:11,050
And one of the things that it does

1607
01:06:11,050 --> 01:06:13,780
is something called smooth pursuit.

1608
01:06:13,780 --> 01:06:18,780
Smooth pursuit is our ability
to track individual objects

1609
01:06:18,960 --> 01:06:21,560
moving, as the name suggests,
smoothly through space

1610
01:06:22,510 --> 01:06:23,983
in various trajectories.

1611
01:06:24,840 --> 01:06:29,840
You can actually train
or improve your vision

1612
01:06:29,980 --> 01:06:32,747
by looking at smooth pursuit stimuli,

1613
01:06:32,747 --> 01:06:34,030
and that sounds really boring.

1614
01:06:34,030 --> 01:06:36,060
What you can do is, and
I'll provide a link to some

1615
01:06:36,060 --> 01:06:37,110
that I think are pretty good

1616
01:06:37,110 --> 01:06:39,440
that are used in various clinics,

1617
01:06:39,440 --> 01:06:42,400
ophthalmology and optometry clinics.

1618
01:06:42,400 --> 01:06:45,040
You can actually take
a few minutes each day,

1619
01:06:45,040 --> 01:06:46,700
or maybe if you don't do it each day,

1620
01:06:46,700 --> 01:06:47,930
you could every third day or so,

1621
01:06:47,930 --> 01:06:50,490
and actually just visually track a ball.

1622
01:06:50,490 --> 01:06:52,630
Sometimes it's moving in and
kind of an infinity symbol.

1623
01:06:52,630 --> 01:06:55,070
Sometimes it's more of a sawtooth.

1624
01:06:55,070 --> 01:06:56,720
Sometimes it's changing speed.

1625
01:06:56,720 --> 01:06:59,820
Sometimes the cue that you're following,

1626
01:06:59,820 --> 01:07:03,380
the little target, is
dilating and contracting.

1627
01:07:03,380 --> 01:07:06,560
This is going to keep the
muscles, I want to be clear,

1628
01:07:06,560 --> 01:07:09,440
this is going to keep
the extraocular muscles

1629
01:07:09,440 --> 01:07:11,240
conditioned and strong

1630
01:07:11,240 --> 01:07:15,500
and allow you to have a
healthy smooth pursuit system.

1631
01:07:15,500 --> 01:07:17,540
Remember, the brain follows the eye.

1632
01:07:17,540 --> 01:07:19,710
It follows the movements of the eye.

1633
01:07:19,710 --> 01:07:20,900
It has to deal with that.

1634
01:07:20,900 --> 01:07:22,620
And the neural circuits within the brain

1635
01:07:22,620 --> 01:07:25,600
have to cope with changes
in smooth pursuit.

1636
01:07:25,600 --> 01:07:27,580
So if you're doing a
lot of reading up close,

1637
01:07:27,580 --> 01:07:28,720
you're not viewing horizons,

1638
01:07:28,720 --> 01:07:31,780
you're not getting a lot of
smooth pursuit type stimulation

1639
01:07:31,780 --> 01:07:35,190
from your life, or you're just getting it

1640
01:07:35,190 --> 01:07:37,360
within the confines of a
little box on your phone,

1641
01:07:37,360 --> 01:07:40,590
like your smooth pursuit is
over, you know, millimeters

1642
01:07:40,590 --> 01:07:43,110
or what we always talk
in terms of visual angle,

1643
01:07:43,110 --> 01:07:44,920
but the amount of degrees of visual angle.

1644
01:07:44,920 --> 01:07:46,370
But if you're just
looking at smooth pursuit

1645
01:07:46,370 --> 01:07:48,070
in this little tiny box on your phone,

1646
01:07:48,070 --> 01:07:49,400
or on your computer screen,

1647
01:07:49,400 --> 01:07:51,470
and you're not looking at
objects in your environment

1648
01:07:51,470 --> 01:07:52,970
like swooping birds and things like that,

1649
01:07:52,970 --> 01:07:53,960
which I'm guessing many of you

1650
01:07:53,960 --> 01:07:55,600
are not spending your time doing,

1651
01:07:55,600 --> 01:07:57,400
well, these mechanisms for smooth pursuit

1652
01:07:57,400 --> 01:07:58,460
will get worse over time.

1653
01:07:58,460 --> 01:07:59,610
Your vision will get worse.

1654
01:07:59,610 --> 01:08:01,610
And so, while I prefer that people

1655
01:08:01,610 --> 01:08:03,110
get out into the real world

1656
01:08:03,110 --> 01:08:07,080
and experience smooth pursuit
tracking of visual objects,

1657
01:08:07,080 --> 01:08:07,913
I don't know, maybe it's a good reason

1658
01:08:07,913 --> 01:08:09,473
to go to a hockey game or, you know,

1659
01:08:09,473 --> 01:08:11,130
and try and keep your eye on the puck,

1660
01:08:11,130 --> 01:08:12,180
which I can never seem to do.

1661
01:08:12,180 --> 01:08:13,920
It moves so fast.

1662
01:08:13,920 --> 01:08:16,569
Or I guess this is a good
reason to watch live sports

1663
01:08:16,569 --> 01:08:18,829
if that's your thing, or
to watch a tennis match,

1664
01:08:18,830 --> 01:08:19,930
like a cat, like a kitten,

1665
01:08:19,930 --> 01:08:21,970
watching the ball go back and forth,

1666
01:08:21,970 --> 01:08:25,080
whatever, watching kids play,
it doesn't really matter.

1667
01:08:25,080 --> 01:08:29,990
The idea is that you want to
use the visual system regularly

1668
01:08:29,990 --> 01:08:31,029
for what it was designed for,

1669
01:08:31,029 --> 01:08:33,479
and smooth pursuit is a great way

1670
01:08:33,479 --> 01:08:36,459
to keep the visual and
motion tracking systems

1671
01:08:36,460 --> 01:08:38,840
of the brain and the eye
and the extraocular muscles

1672
01:08:38,840 --> 01:08:41,149
working in a really
nice coordinate fashion.

1673
01:08:41,149 --> 01:08:44,779
I would say five to 10 minutes,

1674
01:08:44,779 --> 01:08:46,939
three times a week will be great.

1675
01:08:46,939 --> 01:08:47,969
If you care about your vision,

1676
01:08:47,970 --> 01:08:50,210
you can train your vision in this way.

1677
01:08:50,210 --> 01:08:53,580
The other one is to train accommodation.

1678
01:08:53,580 --> 01:08:55,880
There are a lot of videos out
there, I want to be clear,

1679
01:08:55,880 --> 01:09:00,029
on the internet, some of
which are from clinicians,

1680
01:09:00,029 --> 01:09:01,359
some of which are not.

1681
01:09:01,359 --> 01:09:02,639
Some of which are from scientists,

1682
01:09:02,640 --> 01:09:04,609
some of which are from other sources,

1683
01:09:04,609 --> 01:09:07,039
talking about things you can do

1684
01:09:07,040 --> 01:09:09,609
to make your vision better,
to improve your vision.

1685
01:09:09,609 --> 01:09:11,809
Most of those are geared

1686
01:09:11,810 --> 01:09:14,317
toward improving the
extraocular eye muscles,

1687
01:09:14,317 --> 01:09:18,160
but I did consult with
our chair of ophthalmology

1688
01:09:18,160 --> 01:09:21,020
at Stanford School of
Medicine, Jeff Goldberg,

1689
01:09:21,020 --> 01:09:23,810
who's an MD and a PhD,
a phenomenal scientist,

1690
01:09:23,810 --> 01:09:25,640
and a phenomenal clinician,

1691
01:09:25,640 --> 01:09:28,399
and incidentally, a
phenomenal chairman as well,

1692
01:09:28,399 --> 01:09:31,699
about what sorts of things, tools,

1693
01:09:31,700 --> 01:09:35,229
are actually beneficial for
pattern vision and sight,

1694
01:09:35,229 --> 01:09:37,639
because there's just so much
out there on the internet.

1695
01:09:37,640 --> 01:09:40,990
Not all of which is
accurate or good, frankly.

1696
01:09:40,990 --> 01:09:43,970
And he agreed that a
smooth pursuit stimulus,

1697
01:09:43,970 --> 01:09:47,950
that kind of training,
as well as, or exercise,

1698
01:09:47,950 --> 01:09:49,750
as well as near far.

1699
01:09:49,750 --> 01:09:52,210
So spending a few minutes,
you might even just do this

1700
01:09:52,210 --> 01:09:54,960
for two minutes of looking
at something up close,

1701
01:09:54,960 --> 01:09:57,200
that's going to activate these
accommodation mechanisms,

1702
01:09:57,200 --> 01:09:59,270
and then moving it at arms length,

1703
01:09:59,270 --> 01:10:01,400
and focusing on it for five, 10 seconds,

1704
01:10:01,400 --> 01:10:03,870
maybe more, maybe 15 or 20 seconds,

1705
01:10:03,870 --> 01:10:07,510
then slowly moving it into
a location, and then out.

1706
01:10:07,510 --> 01:10:09,740
This is actually a lot
like the visual training

1707
01:10:09,740 --> 01:10:13,770
that's done post-concussion
to try and repair,

1708
01:10:13,770 --> 01:10:16,350
actually repair some of
the balance, and motor,

1709
01:10:16,350 --> 01:10:20,380
and visual, and cognitive
aspects of the brain.

1710
01:10:20,380 --> 01:10:21,850
And we are going to have a guest on

1711
01:10:21,850 --> 01:10:23,570
at a future time that,

1712
01:10:23,570 --> 01:10:26,610
to deal with concussion and
some post-concussion training.

1713
01:10:26,610 --> 01:10:28,750
A lot of post concussion
recovery and training

1714
01:10:28,750 --> 01:10:30,420
centers around the visual system.

1715
01:10:30,420 --> 01:10:33,840
Not just because people are
trying to recover their vision

1716
01:10:33,840 --> 01:10:35,580
and their sense of balance,

1717
01:10:35,580 --> 01:10:37,340
but because, as I mentioned earlier,

1718
01:10:37,340 --> 01:10:40,520
the brain's ability to make
sense of its environment,

1719
01:10:40,520 --> 01:10:42,880
and the brain's ability to parse time,

1720
01:10:42,880 --> 01:10:44,840
not just on the day-night schedule,

1721
01:10:44,840 --> 01:10:49,230
but also shorter time intervals,
follows the visual system.

1722
01:10:49,230 --> 01:10:51,170
Something we'll turn to a
little bit more at the end.

1723
01:10:51,170 --> 01:10:52,100
So what does this mean?

1724
01:10:52,100 --> 01:10:55,750
The tool is, spend two to three minutes

1725
01:10:55,750 --> 01:10:56,870
doing smooth pursuit.

1726
01:10:56,870 --> 01:10:59,076
There's some programs on YouTube,

1727
01:10:59,076 --> 01:11:00,890
or you can just look up
smooth pursuit stimulus,

1728
01:11:00,890 --> 01:11:04,270
and I'll provide a link to
a couple I like as well.

1729
01:11:04,270 --> 01:11:06,640
You could do this with
a pen if you wanted.

1730
01:11:06,640 --> 01:11:07,990
You could do this.

1731
01:11:07,990 --> 01:11:10,040
Someone else could hold a
wand, and you could do that,

1732
01:11:10,040 --> 01:11:11,580
if you've got someone
that can do that for you.

1733
01:11:11,580 --> 01:11:13,310
Practice accommodation for a few minutes,

1734
01:11:13,310 --> 01:11:14,850
maybe every other day,

1735
01:11:14,850 --> 01:11:16,410
just bringing something in close.

1736
01:11:16,410 --> 01:11:18,183
You'll feel the strain
of your eyes doing that.

1737
01:11:18,183 --> 01:11:21,010
I can feel it right now, move it out.

1738
01:11:21,010 --> 01:11:22,550
You'll feel a relaxation point.

1739
01:11:22,550 --> 01:11:24,240
Move it past that relaxation point,

1740
01:11:24,240 --> 01:11:25,073
where you will have to do

1741
01:11:25,073 --> 01:11:26,240
what's called the vergence eye movement

1742
01:11:26,240 --> 01:11:28,670
to maintain focus on that
location as it moves out,

1743
01:11:28,670 --> 01:11:30,100
bring it back in.

1744
01:11:30,100 --> 01:11:32,760
At the point where you
actually have to go cross-eyed,

1745
01:11:32,760 --> 01:11:33,980
this will differ for different people,

1746
01:11:33,980 --> 01:11:35,870
depending on how far apart your eyes are,

1747
01:11:35,870 --> 01:11:37,580
so called interpupillary distance.

1748
