with this kind of stuff when you're a kid.

2000
01:21:12,540 --> 01:21:14,850
If you wear, let's say you
have a Halloween costume

2001
01:21:14,850 --> 01:21:15,960
and you wear an eye patch,

2002
01:21:15,960 --> 01:21:18,000
you're a pirate or
something for Halloween,

2003
01:21:18,000 --> 01:21:19,870
and you cover it up on one side,

2004
01:21:19,870 --> 01:21:21,670
probably for the night
of Halloween, it's okay.

2005
01:21:21,670 --> 01:21:25,150
I do not recommend doing
that recreationally

2006
01:21:25,150 --> 01:21:27,210
if you don't need that
if you're a young child

2007
01:21:27,210 --> 01:21:28,180
or for your child to do that.

2008
01:21:28,180 --> 01:21:31,080
Because, indeed, you create imbalances

2009
01:21:31,080 --> 01:21:33,750
in the brain machinery
that compares information

2010
01:21:33,750 --> 01:21:34,910
coming in through the two eyes,

2011
01:21:34,910 --> 01:21:38,020
and it can shut down
the neural information

2012
01:21:38,020 --> 01:21:40,440
for the occluded, the closed eye.

2013
01:21:40,440 --> 01:21:42,280
Now, I was able to reverse this issue,

2014
01:21:42,280 --> 01:21:44,250
but my binocular vision
has never been terrific.

2015
01:21:44,250 --> 01:21:45,770
I'm much better at the dart board

2016
01:21:45,770 --> 01:21:48,160
and still not very good
if I close one eye.

2017
01:21:48,160 --> 01:21:49,440
I'm much better at the pool table,

2018
01:21:49,440 --> 01:21:52,320
if I close one eye, and
I still am terrible.

2019
01:21:52,320 --> 01:21:55,740
I was the kid in, you
know, in the outfield.

2020
01:21:55,740 --> 01:21:56,840
You know, the ball is coming towards me,

2021
01:21:56,840 --> 01:21:58,210
the ball's coming towards me,
I'm going to catch the ball,

2022
01:21:58,210 --> 01:22:00,540
and like it hit me square in the lip.

2023
01:22:00,540 --> 01:22:03,020
My binocular vision isn't great

2024
01:22:03,020 --> 01:22:05,780
as a consequence of this early event.

2025
01:22:05,780 --> 01:22:09,960
And I have a hard time with
those binocular stereograms,

2026
01:22:09,960 --> 01:22:11,190
those images that are kind of,

2027
01:22:11,190 --> 01:22:12,250
you're supposed to look at them,

2028
01:22:12,250 --> 01:22:15,510
and then the binocular
depth image like pops out.

2029
01:22:15,510 --> 01:22:16,490
All the other kids were going,

2030
01:22:16,490 --> 01:22:18,670
oh, there's the, whatever,
the Statue of Liberty.

2031
01:22:18,670 --> 01:22:21,080
There's the [inaudible], and I see dots.

2032
01:22:21,080 --> 01:22:24,630
Okay, so I have binocular
vision, but I use other cues.

2033
01:22:24,630 --> 01:22:27,430
I use the near-far cues
that I talked about before.

2034
01:22:27,430 --> 01:22:29,750
Motion parallax, the fact
that things are closer to me

2035
01:22:29,750 --> 01:22:32,050
are moving faster than
things further away,

2036
01:22:32,050 --> 01:22:33,780
in order to judge depth.

2037
01:22:33,780 --> 01:22:35,530
And years later, when I got involved in,

2038
01:22:35,530 --> 01:22:37,580
and I don't suggest this for most people,

2039
01:22:39,160 --> 01:22:40,860
I got involved in boxing and martial arts

2040
01:22:40,860 --> 01:22:41,730
when I was younger.

2041
01:22:41,730 --> 01:22:43,480
You sometimes will see fighters,

2042
01:22:43,480 --> 01:22:46,100
this is a slip to avoid getting punched.

2043
01:22:46,100 --> 01:22:48,320
It's also generating motion parallax.

2044
01:22:48,320 --> 01:22:52,690
Many animals judge depth
by moving their head,

2045
01:22:52,690 --> 01:22:56,400
not by using other mechanisms
of accommodation, okay?

2046
01:22:56,400 --> 01:22:59,220
So a lot of birds and monkeys and animals

2047
01:22:59,220 --> 01:23:02,620
will judge depth by moving
their head like this,

2048
01:23:02,620 --> 01:23:04,540
or they'll move from side to side.

2049
01:23:04,540 --> 01:23:06,450
Animals that will undulate sometimes

2050
01:23:06,450 --> 01:23:08,360
are actually doing a depth measurement,

2051
01:23:08,360 --> 01:23:10,090
because as you move from side to side,

2052
01:23:10,090 --> 01:23:12,540
the brain is able to do the math of depth.

2053
01:23:12,540 --> 01:23:14,380
So what does this all mean
in terms of protocols?

2054
01:23:14,380 --> 01:23:15,330
If you're a young person,

2055
01:23:15,330 --> 01:23:18,590
do your best to get really
good binocular vision,

2056
01:23:18,590 --> 01:23:21,020
not just at level of your
phone or your tablet,

2057
01:23:21,020 --> 01:23:22,100
but also at distance,

2058
01:23:22,100 --> 01:23:25,710
you will build strong
binocular visual machinery

2059
01:23:25,710 --> 01:23:27,867
in the brain and at the level of the eyes

2060
01:23:27,867 --> 01:23:30,110
and the eye musculature.

2061
01:23:30,110 --> 01:23:32,820
Now, if you're somebody
who did have an occlusion,

2062
01:23:32,820 --> 01:23:35,170
what's needed is to cover up the other eye

2063
01:23:35,170 --> 01:23:37,050
to create an imbalance,
so that the weak eye,

2064
01:23:37,050 --> 01:23:37,883
the so-called lazy eye,

2065
01:23:37,883 --> 01:23:40,410
this is sometimes
referred to as amblyopia,

2066
01:23:40,410 --> 01:23:42,090
that eye has to work harder.

2067
01:23:42,090 --> 01:23:45,130
So for me, they patched this other eye

2068
01:23:45,130 --> 01:23:46,260
and made this eye,

2069
01:23:46,260 --> 01:23:47,760
eventually, I got vision
through that eye back.

2070
01:23:47,760 --> 01:23:49,140
then they opened them both up.

2071
01:23:49,140 --> 01:23:50,840
Now, you might ask,

2072
01:23:50,840 --> 01:23:53,330
what happens if you cover
both eyes early in life?

2073
01:23:53,330 --> 01:23:54,720
And this is where it gets interesting.

2074
01:23:54,720 --> 01:23:56,280
You might think, well, if covering one eye

2075
01:23:56,280 --> 01:24:00,430
leads to poor vision for that
eye after that eye is open,

2076
01:24:00,430 --> 01:24:03,110
covering both eyes will
probably make you blind, right?

2077
01:24:03,110 --> 01:24:05,130
Actually, that's not what happens.

2078
01:24:05,130 --> 01:24:06,380
What Hubel and Wiesel discovered

2079
01:24:06,380 --> 01:24:09,820
and what's been affirmed
many, many more times over

2080
01:24:09,820 --> 01:24:13,210
in subsequent studies is
that it's competitive,

2081
01:24:13,210 --> 01:24:14,930
that the two eyes are competing

2082
01:24:14,930 --> 01:24:16,510
for real estate up in the brain.

2083
01:24:16,510 --> 01:24:18,790
So if you actually cover both eyes,

2084
01:24:18,790 --> 01:24:23,090
you actually extend the
period of critical plasticity.

2085
01:24:23,090 --> 01:24:24,710
This is a really interesting aspect

2086
01:24:24,710 --> 01:24:26,890
that other people are
starting to leverage now,

2087
01:24:26,890 --> 01:24:29,480
in terms of how to reopen
plasticity later in life.

2088
01:24:29,480 --> 01:24:30,790
But please don't, you know,

2089
01:24:30,790 --> 01:24:33,080
go around with your eyes
covered for too long.

2090
01:24:33,080 --> 01:24:35,130
There are some like retreats and stuff

2091
01:24:35,130 --> 01:24:38,150
where people go into caves
with absolutely no vision.

2092
01:24:38,150 --> 01:24:39,330
It creates hallucinations.

2093
01:24:39,330 --> 01:24:41,470
We'll talk about why
that is in just a moment,

2094
01:24:41,470 --> 01:24:43,130
but here's my suggestion.

2095
01:24:43,130 --> 01:24:45,490
Try and get balanced visual
input through the two eyes.

2096
01:24:45,490 --> 01:24:47,810
Almost everybody has a dominant eye.

2097
01:24:47,810 --> 01:24:50,330
It usually doesn't relate
to your dominant hand,

2098
01:24:50,330 --> 01:24:51,420
although it can.

2099
01:24:51,420 --> 01:24:53,950
And so for me, if I cover up my right eye,

2100
01:24:53,950 --> 01:24:57,000
I see much less well, much more poorly.

2101
01:24:57,000 --> 01:24:58,210
It's a little bit fuzzy,

2102
01:24:58,210 --> 01:24:59,470
and I have to work harder

2103
01:24:59,470 --> 01:25:01,560
in order to see the camera for instance.

2104
01:25:01,560 --> 01:25:03,220
Then, if I cover up my left eye,

2105
01:25:03,220 --> 01:25:04,910
it's actually really easy for me to relax.

2106
01:25:04,910 --> 01:25:06,920
I have a dominant eye.

2107
01:25:06,920 --> 01:25:08,250
Now, you can balance that out

2108
01:25:08,250 --> 01:25:10,950
by covering up the dominant
eye a little bit each day,

2109
01:25:10,950 --> 01:25:12,940
but I would warn any young people,

2110
01:25:12,940 --> 01:25:16,000
meaning, you know, 12 or younger,

2111
01:25:16,000 --> 01:25:18,130
against creating these imbalances

2112
01:25:18,130 --> 01:25:20,410
if there isn't a clinical need to do that.

2113
01:25:20,410 --> 01:25:23,740
And if you do have strong
imbalances between the two eyes,

2114
01:25:23,740 --> 01:25:27,530
which can be caused by
cataract and lens issues,

2115
01:25:27,530 --> 01:25:29,940
can be caused by neuromuscular
issues, et cetera,

2116
01:25:29,940 --> 01:25:32,720
to try and get those dealt
with as early as possible

2117
01:25:32,720 --> 01:25:35,410
by contacting a really
good ophthalmologist

2118
01:25:35,410 --> 01:25:37,700
and ideally a neuro-ophthalmologist.

2119
01:25:37,700 --> 01:25:39,230
It is very normal,

2120
01:25:39,230 --> 01:25:42,620
I should say, it's very common
for young children, babies

2121
01:25:42,620 --> 01:25:45,390
to have an eye that, with strabismus,

2122
01:25:45,390 --> 01:25:48,020
that either deviates
out or that deviates in.

2123
01:25:48,020 --> 01:25:50,180
It is important to correct that.

2124
01:25:50,180 --> 01:25:53,220
If you would like to
have balanced division

2125
01:25:53,220 --> 01:25:54,530
between the two eyes and for the brain

2126
01:25:54,530 --> 01:25:57,410
to respond equally to the two eyes

2127
01:25:57,410 --> 01:26:01,480
and to have, I would say high
fidelity, quality vision.

2128
01:26:01,480 --> 01:26:03,890
Although some people who
have an eye that drifts

2129
01:26:03,890 --> 01:26:06,610
can function normally in life,

2130
01:26:06,610 --> 01:26:09,260
you have an opportunity
early in life to rescue that.

2131
01:26:10,210 --> 01:26:11,770
I won't do, well, maybe I will do this,

2132
01:26:11,770 --> 01:26:14,520
but I can actually relax this eye.

2133
01:26:14,520 --> 01:26:16,160
It's so weak, in some cases,

2134
01:26:16,160 --> 01:26:17,500
that it actually can start to deviate.

2135
01:26:17,500 --> 01:26:18,410
Here, I'll just do this here.

2136
01:26:18,410 --> 01:26:19,243
It's not crossing my eyes.

2137
01:26:19,243 --> 01:26:22,310
So I actually can move my,
I can misalign my eyes,

2138
01:26:22,310 --> 01:26:23,960
because I have to fight very hard

2139
01:26:23,960 --> 01:26:25,810
to have the musculature for this eye,

2140
01:26:26,765 --> 01:26:28,770
keep that eye aligned with the other eye.

2141
01:26:28,770 --> 01:26:30,980
And that's because I've
been doing eye exercises,

2142
01:26:30,980 --> 01:26:32,390
since I was in my twenties,

2143
01:26:32,390 --> 01:26:34,270
'cause I noticed when I would study a lot,

2144
01:26:34,270 --> 01:26:36,280
this eye would start to drift
in, I'd start to see double,

2145
01:26:36,280 --> 01:26:37,240
and I would then, next thing you know,

2146
01:26:37,240 --> 01:26:38,317
I was just covering the eye up,

2147
01:26:38,317 --> 01:26:39,920
and it was getting weaker and weaker,

2148
01:26:39,920 --> 01:26:41,810
just like the atrophy of a muscle.

2149
01:26:41,810 --> 01:26:43,740
So I went to the doctor, what did they do?

2150
01:26:43,740 --> 01:26:45,660
They did the exact wrong thing.

2151
01:26:45,660 --> 01:26:47,860
The optometrist I went to gave me a prism,

2152
01:26:47,860 --> 01:26:50,070
which adjusted it so that I
could see things normally,

2153
01:26:50,070 --> 01:26:51,790
which just made the eye weaker and weaker.

2154
01:26:51,790 --> 01:26:54,640
It's like putting a weak arm into a sling.

2155
01:26:54,640 --> 01:26:58,750
So I had to spend at least
three years of 10 minutes a day,

2156
01:26:58,750 --> 01:27:01,830
is what I recommend, doing near-far,

2157
01:27:01,830 --> 01:27:05,940
covering up my good eye, doing
near-far with my bad eye.

2158
01:27:05,940 --> 01:27:09,410
And now, it's been about 10, 12 years

2159
01:27:09,410 --> 01:27:12,490
that I have pretty
decent binocular vision.

2160
01:27:12,490 --> 01:27:15,400
Now, many of you aren't dealing with this,

2161
01:27:15,400 --> 01:27:17,450
or have these early childhood issues.

2162
01:27:17,450 --> 01:27:19,680
Some of you might be experiencing

2163
01:27:19,680 --> 01:27:22,100
challenges with fatigued eyes

2164
01:27:22,100 --> 01:27:24,300
or with differences in
focus with the two eyes.

2165
01:27:24,300 --> 01:27:26,870
These eye exercises of
near-far, smooth pursuit,

2166
01:27:26,870 --> 01:27:30,010
and checking for dominant
and non-dominant eye

2167
01:27:30,010 --> 01:27:31,460
can be very beneficial.

2168
01:27:31,460 --> 01:27:34,150
I'm again, I'm not a
clinician, so I don't want to,

2169
01:27:34,150 --> 01:27:35,780
you know, give you protocols

2170
01:27:35,780 --> 01:27:37,420
or enforce protocols on anybody.

2171
01:27:37,420 --> 01:27:39,360
You need to figure out what's
right and safe for you,

2172
01:27:39,360 --> 01:27:42,090
given your vision history.

2173
01:27:42,090 --> 01:27:44,390
I do recommend talking to a
really good ophthalmologist

2174
01:27:44,390 --> 01:27:46,690
if you have severe vision
problems of any kind,

2175
01:27:46,690 --> 01:27:49,800
or if you want to offset
vision problems of any kind.

2176
01:27:49,800 --> 01:27:51,210
An optometrist as well,

2177
01:27:51,210 --> 01:27:53,960
but ideally would be a
neuro-ophthalmologist.

2178
01:27:53,960 --> 01:27:56,630
Okay, I did mention hallucinations,

2179
01:27:56,630 --> 01:27:58,697
and they're fun to talk
about and think about.

2180
01:27:58,697 --> 01:28:00,510
And for years, people have asked,

2181
01:28:00,510 --> 01:28:03,320
why do people get visual hallucinations.

2182
01:28:03,320 --> 01:28:04,660
Costello's in sleep right now,

2183
01:28:04,660 --> 01:28:06,720
you can probably hear him
snoring, he's snoring so loud.

2184
01:28:06,720 --> 01:28:07,910
He's probably having hallucinations

2185
01:28:07,910 --> 01:28:11,660
about rabbits, pizza, and
those are mainly his favorite,

2186
01:28:11,660 --> 01:28:12,493
and sleep.

2187
01:28:12,493 --> 01:28:14,413
He's dreaming about sleep in sleep.

2188
01:28:15,450 --> 01:28:18,480
Hallucinations are a property
of the visual system,

2189
01:28:18,480 --> 01:28:21,970
and it was always thought
that hallucinations arise,

2190
01:28:21,970 --> 01:28:24,310
because of over-activation or activation

2191
01:28:24,310 --> 01:28:25,860
of certain aspects of the visual system.

2192
01:28:25,860 --> 01:28:27,450
I just briefly want to mention a paper

2193
01:28:27,450 --> 01:28:28,770
that was published by my good friend

2194
01:28:28,770 --> 01:28:33,070
and phenomenal scientist and
physicist for that matter,

2195
01:28:33,070 --> 01:28:36,630
Cris Niell who's up at the
University of Oregon in Eugene.

2196
01:28:36,630 --> 01:28:38,970
They studied LSD light compounds

2197
01:28:38,970 --> 01:28:42,290
and discovered that
hallucinations actually occur,

2198
01:28:42,290 --> 01:28:46,230
because portions of your
brain become underactive.

2199
01:28:46,230 --> 01:28:49,050
The visual portions of your
brain are under-stimulated.

2200
01:28:49,050 --> 01:28:50,520
This is probably why,

2201
01:28:50,520 --> 01:28:52,580
when people go into these cave retreats,

2202
01:28:52,580 --> 01:28:55,220
something I've never done, I
don't think I ever will do,

2203
01:28:55,220 --> 01:28:56,800
where it's completely black,

2204
01:28:56,800 --> 01:28:58,930
pretty soon, they start hallucinating.

2205
01:28:58,930 --> 01:29:01,910
They start seeing things, even
though there's nothing there.

2206
01:29:01,910 --> 01:29:04,160
The visual system is desperate

2207
01:29:04,160 --> 01:29:06,050
to make guesses about
what's out in the world.

2208
01:29:06,050 --> 01:29:07,570
It's like the eager beaver of your brain.

2209
01:29:07,570 --> 01:29:08,660
It's like, what's out
there, what's out there,

2210
01:29:08,660 --> 01:29:10,270
what's out there?

2211
01:29:10,270 --> 01:29:13,003
Even in low to no vision
people, blind people,

2212
01:29:13,860 --> 01:29:15,580
they are, their brain is
going to be making guesses

2213
01:29:15,580 --> 01:29:17,210
about what's out there
in the auditory world.

2214
01:29:17,210 --> 01:29:20,780
What sounds are there? What
touch sensations are there?

2215
01:29:20,780 --> 01:29:23,430
For sighted folks, it's going to be,

2216
01:29:23,430 --> 01:29:24,970
what's out there in terms of light?

2217
01:29:24,970 --> 01:29:26,190
Light is the dominant way.

2218
01:29:26,190 --> 01:29:27,210
Vision is the dominant way

2219
01:29:27,210 --> 01:29:29,270
that we evaluate the world around us.

2220
01:29:29,270 --> 01:29:31,780
So it turns out that hallucinations

2221
01:29:31,780 --> 01:29:34,250
are an under-activation
of the visual system,

2222
01:29:34,250 --> 01:29:36,880
and then a compensatory, a compensation,

2223
01:29:36,880 --> 01:29:38,010
by which the visual system

2224
01:29:38,010 --> 01:29:41,060
creates activity and hallucinations.

2225
01:29:41,060 --> 01:29:42,680
So if you're in the dark long enough,

2226
01:29:42,680 --> 01:29:44,710
you start to hallucinate and see things.

2227
01:29:44,710 --> 01:29:47,710
So, that's a little note
about hallucinations.

2228
01:29:47,710 --> 01:29:49,890
One of the things that you
can do to improve your vision,

2229
01:29:49,890 --> 01:29:51,540
and it's also kind of fun

2230
01:29:51,540 --> 01:29:55,000
is to put a Snellen chart in your home.

2231
01:29:55,000 --> 01:29:57,010
A Snellen chart is that list of letters.

2232
01:29:57,010 --> 01:29:59,880
Or if you go to the dreaded
Department of Motor Vehicles,

2233
01:29:59,880 --> 01:30:01,160
actually I'm up for renewal soon,

2234
01:30:01,160 --> 01:30:03,610
so I love the Department
of Motor Vehicles.

2235
01:30:03,610 --> 01:30:04,720
The Department of Motor Vehicles,

2236
01:30:04,720 --> 01:30:06,330
they'll have you cover up an eye,

2237
01:30:06,330 --> 01:30:09,470
read the letters on the chart,

2238
01:30:09,470 --> 01:30:11,080
the letters of course
gets smaller and smaller,

2239
01:30:11,080 --> 01:30:13,620
they're trying to figure out
roughly what your vision is.

2240
01:30:13,620 --> 01:30:16,520
Cover up the other eye, you'll do that.

2241
01:30:16,520 --> 01:30:19,620
Some people including nerdy,
vision scientists like me

2242
01:30:19,620 --> 01:30:22,040
have had Snellen charts in their office

2243
01:30:22,040 --> 01:30:24,300
or in their home for many years now,

2244
01:30:24,300 --> 01:30:25,270
and you can just practice,

2245
01:30:25,270 --> 01:30:26,270
and you can see how you're doing

2246
01:30:26,270 --> 01:30:28,630
sitting at a particular distance.

2247
01:30:28,630 --> 01:30:31,240
Your, this is something
that's not often mentioned,

2248
01:30:31,240 --> 01:30:33,080
but your performance on the Snellen chart

2249
01:30:33,080 --> 01:30:36,180
will vary depending on time of day,

2250
01:30:36,180 --> 01:30:38,040
because your level of fatigue

2251
01:30:38,040 --> 01:30:39,930
and your ability to
control that accommodation

2252
01:30:39,930 --> 01:30:42,570
and other mechanisms of
the eye muscles will vary,

2253
01:30:42,570 --> 01:30:44,550
so you can take it as an average.

2254
01:30:44,550 --> 01:30:46,430
It's also a good thing,

2255
01:30:46,430 --> 01:30:48,150
if you're going to get your vision tested

2256
01:30:48,150 --> 01:30:49,744
for corrective lenses,

2257
01:30:49,744 --> 01:30:51,560
or maybe you're going to do laser surgery,

2258
01:30:51,560 --> 01:30:52,610
or something of that sort,

2259
01:30:52,610 --> 01:30:53,810
if you're thinking about any of that,

2260
01:30:53,810 --> 01:30:55,670
to really get it measured
by a professional.

2261
01:30:55,670 --> 01:30:57,906
The ones that you get
in those supermarkets,

2262
01:30:57,906 --> 01:31:01,030
or in many eyeglass stores,

2263
01:31:01,030 --> 01:31:02,260
apologies to the eyeglass stores,

2264
01:31:02,260 --> 01:31:05,473
are often wrong by an order of magnitude.

2265
01:31:06,400 --> 01:31:08,940
And then, when you start
putting corrective lenses on

2266
01:31:08,940 --> 01:31:12,410
that are over-correcting
or under-correcting,

2267
01:31:12,410 --> 01:31:14,240
but more often are over-correcting,

2268
01:31:14,240 --> 01:31:16,220
well, then you're essentially
weakening the system.

2269
01:31:16,220 --> 01:31:17,900
It's like putting a prosthetic on a limb

2270
01:31:17,900 --> 01:31:19,760
that you didn't necessarily need,

2271
01:31:19,760 --> 01:31:22,530
or robot arm when you didn't need

2272
01:31:22,530 --> 01:31:23,650
the use of the robot arm.

2273
01:31:23,650 --> 01:31:25,760
Although now there's so much
excitement about robots,

2274
01:31:25,760 --> 01:31:27,670
I think people are going
to be doing that anyway.

2275
01:31:27,670 --> 01:31:30,090
Nonetheless, get your vision tested

2276
01:31:30,090 --> 01:31:32,130
by somebody who really understands vision,

2277
01:31:32,130 --> 01:31:34,780
like an ophthalmologist or
a really good optometrist.

2278
01:31:35,780 --> 01:31:38,087
If you put a Snellen chart in your home,

2279
01:31:38,087 --> 01:31:41,410
you know, you can do that as
part of your visual training.

2280
01:31:41,410 --> 01:31:43,410
Now, this might seem excessively nerdy,

2281
01:31:43,410 --> 01:31:46,800
but what is more important
than your eyesight, right?

2282
01:31:46,800 --> 01:31:48,050
Eyesight is so vital.

2283
01:31:48,050 --> 01:31:50,730
It's right up there with
movement and our ability to move,

2284
01:31:50,730 --> 01:31:52,410
to generate, to get up out of chairs,

2285
01:31:52,410 --> 01:31:55,280
and to walk and to run, and
to take care of ourselves.

2286
01:31:55,280 --> 01:31:57,910
Eyesight and movement are the main ways

2287
01:31:57,910 --> 01:32:00,660
that we are able to take care of ourselves

2288
01:32:00,660 --> 01:32:01,800
and take care of others.

2289
01:32:01,800 --> 01:32:04,010
When you start having compromised eyesight

2290
01:32:04,010 --> 01:32:06,700
or compromised movement,
people need to take care of us,

2291
01:32:06,700 --> 01:32:08,730
and we become much more challenged

2292
01:32:08,730 --> 01:32:10,360
in moving through our daily life.

2293
01:32:10,360 --> 01:32:11,410
So while it might seem nerdy

2294
01:32:11,410 --> 01:32:13,490
to have a Snellen chart in your home,

2295
01:32:13,490 --> 01:32:16,560
or to do a smooth pursuit
exercise a couple of times a week,

2296
01:32:16,560 --> 01:32:18,190
or to get outside for a few hours a day

2297
01:32:18,190 --> 01:32:20,830
and do your reading or
your laptop work there,

2298
01:32:20,830 --> 01:32:23,270
preserving your eyesight
and preserving your vision

2299
01:32:23,270 --> 01:32:25,680
is one of the most life-enhancing

2300
01:32:25,680 --> 01:32:27,970
or quality of life enhancing
things that you can do.

2301
01:32:27,970 --> 01:32:29,640
And if you're a young person,

2302
01:32:29,640 --> 01:32:32,860
and you can build some of
this into your framework

2303
01:32:32,860 --> 01:32:36,330
of exercise or brain training,
if you want to call it that,

2304
01:32:36,330 --> 01:32:38,690
that can be immensely beneficial
and will really set you up

2305
01:32:38,690 --> 01:32:41,290
to have really good vision
over a long period of time.

2306
01:32:41,290 --> 01:32:42,980
Now, of course, there are genetic factors,

2307
01:32:42,980 --> 01:32:45,330
and there are injury-related factors

2308
01:32:45,330 --> 01:32:48,530
that can compromise eyesight
and our ability to see.

2309
01:32:48,530 --> 01:32:51,640
And, of course, the things
I'm talking about today

2310
01:32:51,640 --> 01:32:53,540
aren't going to solve all those issues,

2311
01:32:53,540 --> 01:32:57,030
but they can have a
tremendous, positive impact

2312
01:32:57,030 --> 01:32:58,920
if you're willing to do
just a little bit of work,

2313
01:32:58,920 --> 01:33:02,710
and none of this is
involving any cost, right?

2314
01:33:02,710 --> 01:33:04,350
It's just time cost.

2315
01:33:04,350 --> 01:33:06,870
So I want, I do want to talk
about a few other things

2316
01:33:06,870 --> 01:33:09,400
that can perhaps improve vision.

2317
01:33:09,400 --> 01:33:11,540
I want to dispel a few myths about stuff

2318
01:33:11,540 --> 01:33:13,570
to take to improve vision.

2319
01:33:13,570 --> 01:33:16,510
And then, I want to just
close by talking about

2320
01:33:16,510 --> 01:33:19,840
how we perceive time using our vision,

2321
01:33:19,840 --> 01:33:21,490
because that will nicely set the stage

2322
01:33:21,490 --> 01:33:24,010
for what we're going to
talk about next episode.

2323
01:33:24,010 --> 01:33:27,580
So now, you understand a lot
about the biology of vision.

2324
01:33:27,580 --> 01:33:29,570
You understand that light
has to arrive at the retina

2325
01:33:29,570 --> 01:33:32,060
and get converted into electrical signals.

2326
01:33:32,060 --> 01:33:36,500
That process requires
things like vitamin A,

2327
01:33:36,500 --> 01:33:38,560
a fat soluble vitamin.

2328
01:33:38,560 --> 01:33:42,100
It requires things like the carotinoids.

2329
01:33:42,100 --> 01:33:46,360
That metabolic cascade,
the biochemical cascade,

2330
01:33:46,360 --> 01:33:47,850
is essential for vision.

2331
01:33:47,850 --> 01:33:49,260
And this is why you've been told

2332
01:33:49,260 --> 01:33:50,930
that carrots help you see better

2333
01:33:50,930 --> 01:33:52,580
'cause they're high in vitamin A.

2334
01:33:53,930 --> 01:33:55,390
There are a few simple things you can do

2335
01:33:55,390 --> 01:33:56,870
to support your vision.

2336
01:33:56,870 --> 01:34:01,870
First of all, it is true
that eating vegetables,

2337
01:34:02,340 --> 01:34:03,890
the dark, leafy vegetables

2338
01:34:03,890 --> 01:34:08,040
and things like carrots that
have vitamin A in abundance,

2339
01:34:08,040 --> 01:34:11,190
and eating them in
close to their raw form,

2340
01:34:11,190 --> 01:34:13,410
so naturally occurring foods

2341
01:34:13,410 --> 01:34:17,380
that contain a lot of
vitamin A in their raw form

2342
01:34:17,380 --> 01:34:19,480
can help support vision.

2343
01:34:19,480 --> 01:34:21,430
Now, does that mean that if you ingest

2344
01:34:21,430 --> 01:34:23,610
super physiological amounts of that stuff,

2345
01:34:23,610 --> 01:34:25,840
that it's going to make your
vision that much better?

2346
01:34:25,840 --> 01:34:29,650
No, but you do need a
threshold level of vitamin A

2347
01:34:29,650 --> 01:34:33,800
in order to see and in order to see well.

2348
01:34:33,800 --> 01:34:36,600
Now, there's a lot of excitement nowadays

2349
01:34:36,600 --> 01:34:39,790
about supplementation to
help support the health

2350
01:34:39,790 --> 01:34:40,810
of the visual system.

2351
01:34:40,810 --> 01:34:43,090
And I'm somebody who's pretty open

2352
01:34:43,090 --> 01:34:45,210
to novel forms of supplementation.

2353
01:34:45,210 --> 01:34:46,250
You've probably gathered that,

2354
01:34:46,250 --> 01:34:48,850
if you've been listening
to this podcast for awhile.

2355
01:34:48,850 --> 01:34:50,830
You have to determine what's safe,

2356
01:34:50,830 --> 01:34:53,300
and economical, and right for you,

2357
01:34:53,300 --> 01:34:55,710
what your risk tolerance is, et cetera.

2358
01:34:55,710 --> 01:34:58,660
But I want to talk about a molecule

2359
01:34:58,660 --> 01:35:01,730
that's in a lot of
supplements to support vision,

2360
01:35:01,730 --> 01:35:05,950
and there are some really good
data on, and that's lutein.

2361
01:35:05,950 --> 01:35:07,640
Now, the study I want to describe

2362
01:35:08,750 --> 01:35:11,340
is actually published in 2016.

2363
01:35:11,340 --> 01:35:13,040
It's from the Journal of Ophthalmology.

2364
01:35:13,040 --> 01:35:15,100
It's a good journal.

2365
01:35:15,100 --> 01:35:16,880
And the title of this paper is,

2366
01:35:16,880 --> 01:35:18,410
it might catch your attention,

2367
01:35:18,410 --> 01:35:22,070
it's "Increased macular
pigment optical density,"

2368
01:35:22,070 --> 01:35:24,110
that just means that macula,

2369
01:35:24,110 --> 01:35:26,950
is an area of the eye for central vision,

2370
01:35:26,950 --> 01:35:28,113
for high acuity vision.

2371
01:35:29,090 --> 01:35:32,817
Pigment density there is
good, you want pigment there.

2372
01:35:32,817 --> 01:35:35,717
"Increase macular pigment optical density

2373
01:35:35,717 --> 01:35:37,010
"and visual acuity,"

2374
01:35:37,010 --> 01:35:40,387
Visual acuity is your ability
to see things in fine detail.

2375
01:35:40,387 --> 01:35:42,680
"Following consumption
of a buttermilk drink

2376
01:35:42,680 --> 01:35:45,710
"containing lutein-enriched egg yolks."

2377
01:35:45,710 --> 01:35:49,200
Remember, raw foods?
Lutein-enriched egg yolks.

2378
01:35:49,200 --> 01:35:50,440
Sounds like a Rocky movie,

2379
01:35:50,440 --> 01:35:52,767
where he would drink the raw egg yolks.

2380
01:35:52,767 --> 01:35:56,200
"A randomized double-blind
placebo controlled trial."

2381
01:35:56,200 --> 01:35:59,500
Now, I'm not suggesting you
go out and eat raw egg yolks.

2382
01:35:59,500 --> 01:36:00,630
There's the risk of salmonella.

2383
01:36:00,630 --> 01:36:01,770
Although, I did hear this,

2384
01:36:01,770 --> 01:36:02,820
someone correct me if I'm wrong,

2385
01:36:02,820 --> 01:36:06,040
but the salmonella is actually
on the outside of the egg,

2386
01:36:06,040 --> 01:36:08,950
not actually in the egg
itself, it's on the shell.

2387
01:36:08,950 --> 01:36:13,330
For reasons that relate to how
that egg got into the world,

2388
01:36:13,330 --> 01:36:15,140
that's where the salmonella lives,

2389
01:36:15,140 --> 01:36:17,350
but I could be wrong about that.

2390
01:36:17,350 --> 01:36:19,750
But raw egg yolks are not something

2391
01:36:19,750 --> 01:36:21,960
that most people want to consume.

2392
01:36:21,960 --> 01:36:23,280
What is this lutein stuff?

2393
01:36:23,280 --> 01:36:27,580
Well, lutein is in the pathway
that relates to vitamin A

2394
01:36:27,580 --> 01:36:32,060
and the formation of the
OPs in the photopigment

2395
01:36:32,060 --> 01:36:33,860
that captures light in
the back of your eye,

2396
01:36:33,860 --> 01:36:37,500
literally absorbs light
pigment in your eye,

2397
01:36:37,500 --> 01:36:39,350
and converts that into electrical signals,

2398
01:36:39,350 --> 01:36:40,570
and allows you to see.

2399
01:36:40,570 --> 01:36:42,380
And there is some evidence,

2400
01:36:42,380 --> 01:36:44,360
I spoke to our chair of ophthalmology,

2401
01:36:44,360 --> 01:36:48,110
there is some evidence through
quality peer-reviewed studies

2402
01:36:48,110 --> 01:36:53,110
that supplementing with
lutein can help offset

2403
01:36:53,480 --> 01:36:56,290
some of the detrimental effects

2404
01:36:56,290 --> 01:36:58,800
of age-related macular degeneration.

2405
01:36:58,800 --> 01:37:03,123
But, I want to emphasize
but, or emphasize however,

2406
01:37:04,690 --> 01:37:07,140
only for individuals with moderate

2407
01:37:07,140 --> 01:37:09,560
to severe macular degeneration.

2408
01:37:09,560 --> 01:37:11,620
For people that have normal vision,

2409
01:37:11,620 --> 01:37:16,620
or with a, just a low-degree
of macular degeneration,

2410
01:37:16,780 --> 01:37:19,330
these studies did not see
a significant improvement

2411
01:37:19,330 --> 01:37:22,020
of vision from supplementing with lutein.

2412
01:37:22,020 --> 01:37:23,020
So, I'm not going to to tell you

2413
01:37:23,020 --> 01:37:24,793
to supplement with lutein or not.

2414
01:37:26,180 --> 01:37:29,480
I don't think any study
is holy, but it does seem

2415
01:37:29,480 --> 01:37:32,650
that if you have moderate to
severe macular degeneration,

2416
01:37:32,650 --> 01:37:33,840
talk to your physician, of course,

2417
01:37:33,840 --> 01:37:35,150
talk to your ophthalmologist,

2418
01:37:35,150 --> 01:37:37,650
I'll always say that, and
I'll say it three times,

2419
01:37:39,190 --> 01:37:42,990
supplementing with lutein
could perhaps support vision

2420
01:37:42,990 --> 01:37:45,040
and offset some vision loss in that case.

2421
01:37:45,040 --> 01:37:47,000
Probably also talk to your ophthalmologist

2422
01:37:47,000 --> 01:37:48,330
or consider the red light therapy

2423
01:37:48,330 --> 01:37:49,750
that I talked about earlier.

2424
01:37:49,750 --> 01:37:51,950
Whereas, if you have normal vision,

2425
01:37:51,950 --> 01:37:55,550
or a low amount of macular degeneration,

2426
01:37:55,550 --> 01:37:57,530
it does not seem, at
least from these studies,

2427
01:37:57,530 --> 01:37:59,760
that lutein had much of an effect.

2428
01:37:59,760 --> 01:38:03,860
Now, I know, and I confess
I'm sort of of the mind

2429
01:38:03,860 --> 01:38:08,860
that if I personally had
age-related macular degeneration,

2430
01:38:09,180 --> 01:38:10,730
or a propensity for it in my family,

2431
01:38:10,730 --> 01:38:15,560
which fortunately I
don't, but in that case,

2432
01:38:15,560 --> 01:38:17,060
I would think that
supplementing with lutein,

2433
01:38:17,060 --> 01:38:20,610
provided it's safe, could
perhaps be of benefit.

2434
01:38:20,610 --> 01:38:22,470
You might want to consider
a low dose of that.

2435
01:38:22,470 --> 01:38:23,840
So again, I'm not pushing any of this

2436
01:38:23,840 --> 01:38:27,910
on anybody by any means,
but you should know that,

2437
01:38:27,910 --> 01:38:30,500
under certain conditions of
severe macular degeneration

2438
01:38:30,500 --> 01:38:31,860
or moderate macular degeneration,

2439
01:38:31,860 --> 01:38:33,430
it does seem like lutein
can be beneficial.

2440
01:38:33,430 --> 01:38:36,090
It does not have to be
consumed through raw egg yolks,

2441
01:38:36,090 --> 01:38:39,900
although that is the
highest density source.

2442
01:38:39,900 --> 01:38:41,670
Cooking the egg yolk, cooking your eggs,

2443
01:38:41,670 --> 01:38:43,490
if you like your scrambled eggs dry,

2444
01:38:43,490 --> 01:38:48,390
or you like your eggs not easy
over or whatever, not runny,

2445
01:38:48,390 --> 01:38:51,030
then you aren't going to get
the benefits of the leucine.

2446
01:38:51,030 --> 01:38:52,430
There are other sources of leucine,

2447
01:38:52,430 --> 01:38:53,920
non-animal sources of leucine as well.

2448
01:38:53,920 --> 01:38:57,030
You can look those up on the internet.

2449
01:38:57,030 --> 01:39:00,830
Now, there are other
compounds that have been shown

2450
01:39:00,830 --> 01:39:03,060
to perhaps be important for offsetting

2451
01:39:03,060 --> 01:39:06,500
or helping different forms of vision loss.

2452
01:39:06,500 --> 01:39:10,880
One is, I'm going to spell
this out, I-D-E-B-E-N-O-N-E,

2453
01:39:10,880 --> 01:39:14,900
idebenone, idebenone, idebenone,

2454
01:39:14,900 --> 01:39:17,433
I can never pronounce these
compounds, forgive me,

2455
01:39:18,370 --> 01:39:20,460
unless I've worked with them.

2456
01:39:20,460 --> 01:39:22,630
There is evidence that
it can be beneficial

2457
01:39:22,630 --> 01:39:27,570
for Leber's congenital eye disease.

2458
01:39:27,570 --> 01:39:30,020
I would definitely go on to examine.com,

2459
01:39:30,020 --> 01:39:32,730
put in I-D-E-B-N-O-N-E.

2460
01:39:32,730 --> 01:39:36,590
And for things like
Leber's optic neuropathies,

2461
01:39:36,590 --> 01:39:39,670
which is a degenerative
condition of the eye,

2462
01:39:39,670 --> 01:39:40,560
whether or not people should

2463
01:39:40,560 --> 01:39:43,270
just be taking this stuff anyway
is still an open question.

2464
01:39:43,270 --> 01:39:45,290
There aren't a lot of studies about it.

2465
01:39:45,290 --> 01:39:46,870
A lot of people that are interested

2466
01:39:46,870 --> 01:39:49,410
in taking things to support their vision

2467
01:39:49,410 --> 01:39:52,193
are taking lutein as a
preventative measure.

2468
01:39:53,380 --> 01:39:55,400
I don't pass any judgment
one way or the other.

2469
01:39:55,400 --> 01:39:57,610
Typically, those supplements

2470
01:39:57,610 --> 01:40:02,550
also include the zeaxanthins
and astaxanthins.

2471
01:40:02,550 --> 01:40:05,670
Okay, the pronunciation of
this is terrible, I'm sure,

2472
01:40:05,670 --> 01:40:07,050
but that's not too far off,

2473
01:40:07,050 --> 01:40:12,050
but basically Z-E-A-X-A-N-T-H-I-N.

2474
01:40:12,830 --> 01:40:13,820
You can see why it's hard to pronounce,

2475
01:40:13,820 --> 01:40:17,020
Z-E-A-X-A-N-T-H-I-N.

2476
01:40:17,020 --> 01:40:21,450
And the other one is
A-S-T-A-X-A-N-T-H-I-N.

2477
01:40:21,450 --> 01:40:24,440
Both of these have been shown, excuse me,

2478
01:40:24,440 --> 01:40:26,180
both of these have been shown

2479
01:40:26,180 --> 01:40:30,860
to offset some of the disruption in vision

2480
01:40:30,860 --> 01:40:32,770
that occurs with aging.

2481
01:40:32,770 --> 01:40:35,320
What is astaxanthin?

2482
01:40:35,320 --> 01:40:37,440
It's a really interesting compound.

2483
01:40:37,440 --> 01:40:41,170
It's the red-pink pigment
found in various seafoods.

2484
01:40:41,170 --> 01:40:43,910
So shrimp, I'm not a big seafood fan,

2485
01:40:43,910 --> 01:40:46,060
but like certain fish, like the,

2486
01:40:46,060 --> 01:40:47,230
you'll see at the fish market

2487
01:40:47,230 --> 01:40:49,510
will have that red-pink pigment.

2488
01:40:49,510 --> 01:40:51,770
And it's also in the
feathers of flamingos,

2489
01:40:51,770 --> 01:40:54,270
please don't eat the
feathers of flamingos,

